name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: Man when i took these out of the box i thought "oh what plastic crap have i ordered" however they are super small, light and was able to connect all data cables with no issues. Flat base easy to use mounting tape on. All in all suited my purpose of home networking. they dont run hot under load as well.

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: Great little product, works right of the box, no need for set up. Connect the land line and power and it's ready to go. If you're looking at other RJ45 splitters with no power supply, don't bother. Buy this one instead. I've got those cheap under $8 "Y" shaped splitters and they don't work. This one works great. Mind it can connect up to 4 devices at the same time, one of the slots is for the land line.

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: These switches are pretty awesome and great value for money, they're almost as cheap as unbranded switches, but are actually from a known brand. They're also very stable, I've never had to reboot them because of a network issue. In terms of speed, I was initially confused as I was only getting around 500 mbps during file transfers, but as it turned out, Windows file sharing kind of sux, I've since switched to doing file transfers over SSH/SFTP and now I get the full gigabit speed this switch supports. I've actually purchased three of the 5 port switches and one 8 port switch, so that should be an indication of how much I like these switches. Be very careful when buying, the white version is not just cheaper because of its colour, it's a 100mbps switch, not a gigabit switch like the black one. Also remember to get CAT6 cables so you get the full speed these switches offer.

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: I thought to let those contemplating this little switch to BUY IT.Its a tiny little thing and honestly, beyond belief at the price.I bought it on the xmas specials for under the TV cabinet. I've an old laptop there (with a USB HDD) that is used as a PiHole server and SAMBA media server. The TV and Lappie were on wifi, but as we are in a building it became congested sometimes.This tiny little thing absolute fits the bill. Utterly silent, with only a tiny green light to show its powered.Chucked it down the back of the cabinet and now have Gigabit Ethernet to to whole unit :)

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: I used this to give myself more Ethernet ports to run to multuple devices including an Xbox, PC, Playstaion, Laptop and Router. It works really well and has very high speeds. It worked well with my internet as I was constantly getting 100mbs across all devices. The box itself is quite small only being about 15cm x 8cm. It requires a direct connection to an outlet so make sure you have one available. You can put the Ethernet cable from your modem into any of the ports and it will still work. Great value for money and solved my problem!

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: 'Out of the box' it just worked -  I had added a wireless extender downstairs to my upstairs office modem and wanted to update the old 'ethernet over power' for my Smart TV and devices (BlueRay Player, Amp, Fetch TV and the like) - this unit plugged straight into the wireless extender - cables clicked into it from the devices - and it just worked, faster than ever - Wireless covering the whole house and the entertainment system all direct connected with 10/100 ethernet cables - excellent product at a great price.

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: Bought this and was working great, until a little more after a month the ethernet stopped working. It worked for a little bit when I unplugged and plugged it back in but then nothing. I then plugged the ethernet straight into my PC and it was lightning fast. it was definitely the switch.Amazon wont give me a refund for the defective product. Please don't make the same mistake I did. Get something a bit more expensive (there is a D-link or Netgear just slightly more than this one). This is trash.

name: TP-Link LiteWave 5-Port Gigabit Desktop Switch, Plastic Case, 0/100/1000Mbps, Networking Switch, Auto-Negotiation, RJ45 Port, Plug and Play (LS1005G)
reviews: I had high hopes for this device since it's cheap, quiet (fanless), low power and tiny (cigarette box size).Unfortunately while the device is plug and play, without management there is no way to deal with any bad switch  behaviour. In this case, prosumer clients - with logging of interface changes, that were completely stable on a 10/100 hub reported link transitions multiple times (between 5 and 10) a day.Since the purpose of the device was to increase throughput for video storage and playback (from the successor to the ReadyNAS NAS), link transitions are unacceptable.While the switch purchase was a disappointment, Amazon and Australia Post (return delivery) excelled themselves. Aus Post had the parcel back to Amazon in less than 2 days and Amazon had processed the refund in less than a day afterward (the purchase price was credited to my account about 2 days after I put the parcel in the letter box.)I have decided after this experience that a small 2nd hand enterprise switch (those famous names like Cisco) is better suited to my needs.
